            <h2>Introduction to Stacks</h2>
            <p>A stack is a linear data structure that follows the Last In, First Out (LIFO) principle. Elements are added and removed from the top of the stack, making it useful for various applications such as function call management and expression evaluation.</p>
            
            <h2>Why Use Stacks?</h2>
            <p>Stacks are beneficial because they provide:</p>
            <ul>
                <li>Simple and efficient LIFO access to elements.</li>
                <li>Easy implementation for undo mechanisms in applications.</li>
                <li>Support for recursive function calls in programming languages.</li>
            </ul>
            
            <h2>Common Operations</h2>
            <p>Common operations on stacks include:</p>
            <ul>
                <li>Pushing elements onto the stack.</li>
                <li>Popping elements from the stack.</li>
                <li>Peeking at the top element without removing it.</li>
                <li>Checking if the stack is empty.</li>
            </ul>
        </div>
